You’ve got the Laurent expansion exactly right. Here’s the clean statement, plus the key facts most people forget (definitions, convergence, values, and the Hurwitz generalization):

The Laurent expansion at s = 1

\boxed{\;\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^n\,\gamma_n}{n!}\,(s-1)^n\;}
\qquad(\gamma_0\equiv \gamma\ \text{is Euler–Mascheroni})

So written out:
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\gamma-\gamma_1(s-1)+\frac{\gamma_2}{2}(s-1)^2-\frac{\gamma_3}{6}(s-1)^3+\cdots

What the coefficients are

The (Stieltjes) constants \gamma_n can be defined by the limit
\boxed{\;\gamma_n=\lim_{m\to\infty}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{m}\frac{(\log k)^n}{k}-\frac{(\log m)^{n+1}}{n+1}\right)\;}
and they’re exactly the Taylor coefficients of \zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1} at s=1:
\gamma_n=(-1)^n\,\left.\frac{d^n}{ds^n}\Big(\zeta(s)-\tfrac{1}{s-1}\Big)\right|_{s=1}.

Convergence radius (often misstated)

\zeta(s) is meromorphic on \mathbb{C} with a single simple pole at s=1. Hence the analytic part
\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1} is entire, so its Taylor series about s=1 has infinite radius of convergence.
Equivalently, the Laurent series above converges for all s\neq 1. (It may converge slowly when |s-1| is large.)

First few numerical values (for orientation)

\gamma_0=\gamma\approx 0.5772156649,\quad
\gamma_1\approx -0.0728158455,\quad
\gamma_2\approx -0.0096903632,\quad
\gamma_3\approx 0.0020538344.
(Signs alternate in no simple pattern beyond the factor (-1)^n already built into the series.)

Quick usage near s=1

Let s=1+\varepsilon with |\varepsilon|\ll 1:
\zeta(1+\varepsilon)=\frac{1}{\varepsilon}+\gamma-\gamma_1\,\varepsilon+\frac{\gamma_2}{2}\varepsilon^2-\frac{\gamma_3}{6}\varepsilon^3+O(\varepsilon^4).
Truncating after the \varepsilon or \varepsilon^2 term is typically accurate for small |\varepsilon|.

Hurwitz generalization (worth knowing)

For the Hurwitz zeta \zeta(s,a) (with a\not\in \{0,-1,-2,\dots\}):
\boxed{\;\zeta(s,a)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^n\,\gamma_n(a)}{n!}\,(s-1)^n\,,\qquad \gamma_n(1)=\gamma_n\;}
These \gamma_n(a) are the generalized Stieltjes constants, recovering the classical ones at a=1.

